me. A range of prominent criminologists offers diverse views in fifteen original essays, providing students with the first proper assessment of self-control theory. This lucid book addresses important general considerations relevant to the theory, its relationship to other theories of crime, and its relevance to different types of crime. The book ends with a response from the originators of the theory, who tackle their critics' concerns and offer new explanations and revisions. This compelling text will be an asset for academics, researchers, and students interested in explaining criminal behavior.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 4aLaw -- Law and Society. 4aSociology -- Law and Criminology. 4aSociology -- Theory and Methods. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Criminology.2bisacsh1 aAkers, Ronald L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeaver, Kevin M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCullen, Francis T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFelson, Richard B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFriedrichs, David O., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGeis, Gilbert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoode, Erich, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoode, Erich, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGottfredson, Michael R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreenberg, David F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHirschi, Travis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIovanni, LeeAnn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMatsueda, Ross L., econtributor.4c